Wow!  Am I glad I happened on to this discussion.  If I may, I would
like to offer some comments.  For several years I have been bothered
by many of the *constants* used to help explain or amplify
cosmological and quantum phenomenae.  The one constant that has
bothered me the most was c.  It seems quite presumptive of us, as
predominately visual beings, to think that we have *seen* a limit to
the speed of light and therefore, to informational exchange.  If c is
truly a constant, then there is a multiplicative equivalence between
energy and mass as Einstein proposed.  I realized that the universe
must be a combination of either energy or mass and that their
relationship was directly intertwined.  I concluded that matter can be
explained as transformations of this universal energy (your aether).
I also think that there are some problems with our view of time.  Its
unidirectionality and liniarity present unique problems.  I am
wrestling with the notion that each particle/event has its own time
signature which makes that particle/event unique and that specific
time signature is needed to completely define it.  (I agree that
action at a distance is a non-problem when we consider the previously
defined properties of the aether as a whole.)  Quantum states,
strings, and galaxy clusters seem more easilly related when viewed in
the context of an all-permeating aether.  Magueijo's Variable Speed of
Light (VLS) theory, while innovative, becomes unnecessary in the
context of an aether.  Thanks for posting your thoughts.  I'm relieved
to find others thinking along the same track.

Lloyd Hekhuis
